<paragraph id="EC1E1D0F4D2CF86AFF2C5ECFCF8F5A27" blockId="25.[151,1437,710,1495]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<keyLead id="5750BE3A4D2CF86AFF2C5ECFCF8F5A27" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
1. Antennomere 4 without tomentose pubescence (
<figureCitation id="749A018A4D2CF86AFD145ECFC8EC5BEA" box="[687,767,710,732]" captionStart="FIGURES 15–18" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1510,1534]" captionTargetBox="[169,1311,186,1480]" captionTargetId="figure-23@10.[156,1432,181,1486]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 15–18. Xanthopygus luctuosus (Blanchard). 15. Habitus photograph. 16. Pronotum. 17. Sternites 6–8. 18. Antenna. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048493" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048493/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Figs. 18</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="749A018A4D2CF86AFCB25ECFC9375BED" box="[777,804,710,732]" captionStart="FIGURES 37–39" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1645,1669]" captionTargetBox="[291,1287,385,1614]" captionTargetId="figure-122@16.[281,1307,381,1621]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 37–39. Xanthopygus oliveirae Lynch. 37. Habitus photograph. 38. Pronotum. 39. Antenna. The pronotum of this specimen is depressed dorsally (probably due to preservation). Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048509/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">39</figureCitation>
); mandibles more or less straight except tip (
<figureCitation id="749A018A4D2CF86AFB6A5ECFCF325BED" box="[1233,1313,710,732]" captionStart="FIGURES 15–18" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1510,1534]" captionTargetBox="[169,1311,186,1480]" captionTargetId="figure-23@10.[156,1432,181,1486]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 15–18. Xanthopygus luctuosus (Blanchard). 15. Habitus photograph. 16. Pronotum. 17. Sternites 6–8. 18. Antenna. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048493" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048493/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Figs. 15</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="749A018A4D2CF86AFA905ECFCF555BED" box="[1323,1350,710,732]" captionStart="FIGURES 37–39" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1645,1669]" captionTargetBox="[291,1287,385,1614]" captionTargetId="figure-122@16.[281,1307,381,1621]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 37–39. Xanthopygus oliveirae Lynch. 37. Habitus photograph. 38. Pronotum. 39. Antenna. The pronotum of this specimen is depressed dorsally (probably due to preservation). Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048509/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">37</figureCitation>
); eyes as long as 1/4 length of head (
<figureCitation id="749A018A4D2CF86AFE575EEDC82E5BC8" box="[492,573,739,762]" captionStart="FIGURES 15–18" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1510,1534]" captionTargetBox="[169,1311,186,1480]" captionTargetId="figure-23@10.[156,1432,181,1486]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 15–18. Xanthopygus luctuosus (Blanchard). 15. Habitus photograph. 16. Pronotum. 17. Sternites 6–8. 18. Antenna. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048493" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048493/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Figs. 15</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="749A018A4D2CF86AFDFC5EEDC8715BCB" box="[583,610,740,762]" captionStart="FIGURES 37–39" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1645,1669]" captionTargetBox="[291,1287,385,1614]" captionTargetId="figure-122@16.[281,1307,381,1621]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 37–39. Xanthopygus oliveirae Lynch. 37. Habitus photograph. 38. Pronotum. 39. Antenna. The pronotum of this specimen is depressed dorsally (probably due to preservation). Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048509/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">37</figureCitation>
); head appearing flat (
<figureCitation id="749A018A4D2CF86AFC875EEDC99E5BC8" box="[828,909,739,762]" captionStart="FIGURES 15–18" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1510,1534]" captionTargetBox="[169,1311,186,1480]" captionTargetId="figure-23@10.[156,1432,181,1486]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 15–18. Xanthopygus luctuosus (Blanchard). 15. Habitus photograph. 16. Pronotum. 17. Sternites 6–8. 18. Antenna. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048493" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048493/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Figs. 15</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="749A018A4D2CF86AFC2C5EEDC9A15BCB" box="[919,946,740,762]" captionStart="FIGURES 37–39" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1645,1669]" captionTargetBox="[291,1287,385,1614]" captionTargetId="figure-122@16.[281,1307,381,1621]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 37–39. Xanthopygus oliveirae Lynch. 37. Habitus photograph. 38. Pronotum. 39. Antenna. The pronotum of this specimen is depressed dorsally (probably due to preservation). Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048509/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">37</figureCitation>
); sternite 6 with two anterior transverse lines (
<figureCitation id="749A018A4D2CF86AFACE5EEDCAE85A26" captionStart="FIGURES 15–18" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1510,1534]" captionTargetBox="[169,1311,186,1480]" captionTargetId="figure-23@10.[156,1432,181,1486]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 15–18. Xanthopygus luctuosus (Blanchard). 15. Habitus photograph. 16. Pronotum. 17. Sternites 6–8. 18. Antenna. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048493" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048493/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
)................................................................................................ 2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="EC1E1D0F4D2CF86AFF2C5F17CF8F5A5F" blockId="25.[151,1437,710,1495]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<keyLead id="5750BE3A4D2CF86AFF2C5F17CF8F5A5F" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<emphasis id="DED5C11D4D2CF86AFF2C5F17CA8C5A02" bold="true" box="[151,159,798,819]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">-</emphasis>
Antennomere 4 with tomentose pubescence (Figs. 10, 26, 33, 43, 50); mandibles curved from apical half (
<figureCitation id="749A018A4D2CF86AFB6E5F17CF225A02" box="[1237,1329,798,820]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1474,1498]" captionTargetBox="[158,1430,525,1451]" captionTargetId="figure-165@3.[158,1430,525,1451]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Xanthopygus xanthopygus (Nordmann). 1. Dorsal view of left mandible, scale bar = 2.1 mm. 2. Dorsal view of the right mandible, scale bar = 2.1 mm. 3. Maxilla, scale bar = 1.0 mm. 4. Hypopharynx and labial palps, scale bar = 0.8 mm. 5. Prosternum, scale bar = 1.8 mm. 6. Meso- and metaventrite, scale bar = 2.6 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048485" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048485/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
Figs. 1 
<emphasis id="DED5C11D4D2CF86AFAAC5F17CF305A02" bold="true" box="[1303,1315,798,819]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">–</emphasis>
2
</figureCitation>
, 7, 40, 47); eyes as long as 1/3-2/5 length of head (Figs. 7, 23, 30, 40, 47); head appearing convex (Figs. 7, 23, 30, 40, 47); sternite 6 with single anterior transverse line (Fig. 9)..................................................................... 3
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="575505AA4D2CF86AFF2C5F7FCF8F5AD2" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<paragraph id="EC1E1D0F4D2CF86AFF2C5F7FCF8E5A98" blockId="25.[151,1437,710,1495]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<keyLead id="5750BE3A4D2CF86AFF2C5F7FCF8E5A98" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
2. Antennomere 3 clearly longer than 2 (
<figureCitation id="749A018A4D2CF86AFDE25F7FC8B15ABD" box="[601,674,886,908]" captionStart="FIGURES 15–18" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1510,1534]" captionTargetBox="[169,1311,186,1480]" captionTargetId="figure-23@10.[156,1432,181,1486]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 15–18. Xanthopygus luctuosus (Blanchard). 15. Habitus photograph. 16. Pronotum. 17. Sternites 6–8. 18. Antenna. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048493" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048493/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
); pronotum microsculpture polygon shaped; tergite 6 sparsely punctate; tip of paramere emarginate (
<figureCitation id="749A018A4D2CF86AFE035F9DC83F5A9B" box="[440,556,916,938]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–21" captionStartId="11.[151,264,782,806]" captionTargetBox="[197,1385,181,753]" captionTargetId="figure-16@11.[197,1390,181,758]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 19–21. Aedeagus of X. luctuosus (Blanchard). 19. Dorsal view. 20. Lateral view. 21. Detail of paramere, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048495" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048495/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Figs. 19, 21</figureCitation>
).............................................................. 
<taxonomicName id="2BA1668C4D2CF86AFA9C5F9DCF8E5A98" box="[1319,1437,916,937]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Staphylinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="176" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luctuosus">
<emphasis id="DED5C11D4D2CF86AFA9C5F9DCF8E5A98" box="[1319,1437,916,937]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">X. luctuosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="EC1E1D0F4D2CF86AFF2C5FB8CF8F5AD2" blockId="25.[151,1437,710,1495]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<keyLead id="5750BE3A4D2CF86AFF2C5FB8CF8F5AD2" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
- Antennomere 3 subequal to 2 (
<figureCitation id="749A018A4D2CF86AFDA85FB8C84F5AF6" box="[531,604,945,967]" captionStart="FIGURES 37–39" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1645,1669]" captionTargetBox="[291,1287,385,1614]" captionTargetId="figure-122@16.[281,1307,381,1621]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 37–39. Xanthopygus oliveirae Lynch. 37. Habitus photograph. 38. Pronotum. 39. Antenna. The pronotum of this specimen is depressed dorsally (probably due to preservation). Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048509/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Fig. 39</figureCitation>
); pronotum microsculpture with transverse lines; tergite 6 densely punctate; no male specimens known............................................................................ 
<taxonomicName id="2BA1668C4D2CF86AFA975FC6CF8F5AD2" box="[1324,1436,974,996]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Xanthopygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="176" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oliveirae">
<emphasis id="DED5C11D4D2CF86AFA975FC6CF8F5AD2" box="[1324,1436,974,996]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">X. oliveirae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="575505AA4D2CF86AFF2C5FE5CF8F5D68" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<paragraph id="EC1E1D0F4D2CF86AFF2C5FE5CF8F5D2F" blockId="25.[151,1437,710,1495]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<keyLead id="5750BE3A4D2CF86AFF2C5FE5CF8F5D2F" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
3. Antennomere 4 longer than wide (
<figureCitation id="749A018A4D2CF86AFD8E5FE5C86A5D30" box="[565,633,1003,1026]" captionStart="FIGURES 47–50" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1921,1945]" captionTargetBox="[151,1430,601,1891]" captionTargetId="figure-211@22.[149,1437,597,1897]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 47–50. Xanthopygus xanthopygus (Nordmann). 47. Habitus photograph. 48. Pronotum. 49. Sternites 6–8. 50. Antenna. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048518" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048518/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Fig 50</figureCitation>
); pronotum densely punctate, typically with three rows of punctures on each half beside median line (
<figureCitation id="749A018A4D2CF86AFE185800CBF85D2E" box="[419,491,1033,1055]" captionStart="FIGURES 47–50" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1921,1945]" captionTargetBox="[151,1430,601,1891]" captionTargetId="figure-211@22.[149,1437,597,1897]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 47–50. Xanthopygus xanthopygus (Nordmann). 47. Habitus photograph. 48. Pronotum. 49. Sternites 6–8. 50. Antenna. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048518" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048518/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Fig. 48</figureCitation>
); sternite 
<quantity id="2B59B0EA4D2CF86AFDF25800C87D5D2E" box="[585,622,1033,1055]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.778" pageId="25" pageNumber="176" unit="in" value="7.0">7 in</quantity>
males with porose structure (
<figureCitation id="749A018A4D2CF86AFC315800C9DC5D2E" box="[906,975,1033,1055]" captionStart="FIGURES 47–50" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1921,1945]" captionTargetBox="[151,1430,601,1891]" captionTargetId="figure-211@22.[149,1437,597,1897]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 47–50. Xanthopygus xanthopygus (Nordmann). 47. Habitus photograph. 48. Pronotum. 49. Sternites 6–8. 50. Antenna. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048518" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048518/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Fig. 49</figureCitation>
)........................ 
<taxonomicName id="2BA1668C4D2CF86AFAB35803CF8F5D2F" baseAuthorityName="Nordmann" baseAuthorityYear="1837" box="[1288,1436,1033,1055]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Xanthopygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="176" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xanthopygus">
<emphasis id="DED5C11D4D2CF86AFAB35803CF8F5D2F" box="[1288,1436,1033,1055]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">X. xanthopygus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="EC1E1D0F4D2CF86AFF2C582ECF8F5D68" blockId="25.[151,1437,710,1495]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<keyLead id="5750BE3A4D2CF86AFF2C582ECF8F5D68" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
- Antennomere 4 subquadrate (Figs. 10, 26, 33, 43); pronotum not densely punctate, typically with two or less rows of punctures on each half beside median line (Figs. 8, 24, 31, 41); sternite 
<quantity id="2B59B0EA4D2CF86AFC95584DC9405D6B" box="[814,851,1092,1114]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.778" pageId="25" pageNumber="176" unit="in" value="7.0">7 in</quantity>
males without porose structure (Figs. 9, 25, 32, 42)..... 4
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="575505AA4D2CF86AFF2C5868CF8F5DDD" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<paragraph id="EC1E1D0F4D2CF86AFF2C5868CF8F5D80" blockId="25.[151,1437,710,1495]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
